However, the R-squared value is only about 0.55, which means that our model is only predicting about 55% of the variation of prices of baseball cards. To make this model more accurate, I will investigate some of the relationships between our explanatory and response variables.

Refining the Model

# Second Model
lm_second <- lm(log(Price) ~ (Player_Popularity) + (Rookie_Card) + Card_Grade + Brand + Year + (Limited_Edition) + (Autographed) + (Market_Demand),
              data=baseball_cards)
summary(lm_second)

The model above regresses the natural logarithm of the price of baseball cards on the explanatory variables of player popularity, rookie status, card grade, card brand, year, limited edition status, autographed status, and market demand. Compared to the base model, this second model is able to predict more variation in the price of baseball cards, as the r-squared value is higher. Using these explanatory variables, the model can predict about 73% of the variation in the log price of baseball cards. It seems that all of these explanatory variables are significant in predicting a cards price excpet for the card brand and card grade. This model can be used to predict the price by transforming the response variable back to price.

Predictions Using the Model

# Predictions Using Final Model
baseball_cards <- baseball_cards %>% 
  mutate(
    predictions = (exp(predict(lm_second,baseball_cards)))
  )

# Residuals- difference between actual price and predicted price
baseball_cards <- baseball_cards %>% 
  mutate(residuals = (Price - predictions), baseball_cards)

Now, in the baseball cards data set we have a column called predictions, which is the predicted price of the baseball card based on our model. We also have a column called residuals, which is the difference between the actual price and our models predicted price. An ideal model would produce very low residual values because this means the predictions are very close to the actual values.

#Plotting the predicted vs. actual values
plot(exp(predict(lm_second)), baseball_cards$Price, 
     xlab = "Predicted Prices", 
     ylab = "Actual Prices")
     abline(a = 0, b = 1, lwd=2, col = "red")

The graph above helps us see that our model does fairly well at predicting the price of baseball cards that are a lower price, but the errors in our predictions get larger as we see higher prices of baseball cards.

Splitting Data into Testing/Training Sets

set.seed(20240301)

training_idx <- sample(nrow(baseball_cards),size=round(nrow(baseball_cards)*0.8),replace=F)
testing_idx <- (1:nrow(baseball_cards))[!(1:nrow(baseball_cards)) %in% training_idx]
training_data <- baseball_cards[training_idx,]
testing_data <- baseball_cards[testing_idx,]

refit_final <- update(lm_second,data=training_data)

# Using this model to predict prices
testing_data <- testing_data %>% 
  mutate(
    new_predictions = exp(predict(refit_final,testing_data)),
    residuals = Price - new_predictions
  )

#Plotting the new predicted vs. actual values

ggplot(testing_data,
       aes(x= (new_predictions), y = (Price))) +
  geom_line() + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  labs(x="Predicted Price",
       y="Actual price",
       title="New Price Predictions") +
  scale_y_continuous(label=dollar) +
  scale_x_continuous(label=dollar)

The plot above shows the comparison of the new predicted values with the updated model in comparison to the true prices, which shows this model is best when predicting lower priced baseball cards. However, with baseball cards of at higher price levels, the predictions might become less accurate. Finally, we can look at the residuals, which are the differences in price between the models predictions and the actual price.

ggplot(testing_data,
       aes(x= (Price), y = (residuals))) +
  geom_line() + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  labs(x="Price",
       y="Residuals",
       title="Residuals by Price") +
  scale_y_continuous(label=dollar) +
  scale_x_continuous(label=dollar)

This visual is helpful in understanding the success of our model, and it is clear that for baseball cards that are less than about $5,000, our model is fairly accurate because the residuals are close to 0. However, as the price increases, our predictions on the price of baseball cards becomes less accurate.

#Create a training and testing dataset

bound <- floor((nrow(baseball_cards)/2))

tree <- rpart(log(Price) ~ (Player_Popularity) + (Rookie_Card) + Card_Grade + Brand + Year + (Limited_Edition) + (Autographed) + Market_Demand, method = "class",
              data=data.train)

######
#ROC Curve
#The only think you need to change below is: 
#1) the name of your datasets. For example, grad.test$ below should be the name of your testing dataset.  
#2) On lines 99 and 100, the 1 and 0 should reflect the values of your depedent variable.

# for ROC curve we need probabilties so we can sort grad.test
data.test$probs <- predict(tree,data.test, type="prob")[,2] # returns prob of both cats, just need 1

roc.data <- data.frame(cutoffs = c(1,sort(unique(data.test$probs),decreasing=T)),
                       TP.at.cutoff = 0,
                       TN.at.cutoff = 0)

for(i in 1:dim(roc.data)[1]){
  this.cutoff <- roc.data[i,"cutoffs"]
  roc.data$TP.at.cutoff[i] <- sum(data.test[data.test$probs >= this.cutoff,depvariable] == 1)
  roc.data$TN.at.cutoff[i] <- sum(data.test[data.test$probs < this.cutoff,depvariable] == 0)
}
roc.data$TPR <- roc.data$TP.at.cutoff/max(roc.data$TP.at.cutoff) 
roc.data$Specificity <- roc.data$TN.at.cutoff/max(roc.data$TN.at.cutoff) 
roc.data$FPR <- 1 - roc.data$Specificity

with(roc.data,
     plot(x=FPR,
          y=TPR,
          type = "l",
          xlim=c(0,1),
          ylim=c(0,1),
          main="ROC Curve'")     
)
abline(c(0,1),lty=2)
